var __index = {"config":{"lang":["en"],"separator":"[\\s\\-]+","pipeline":["stopWordFilter"],"fields":{"title":{"boost":1000.0},"text":{"boost":1.0},"tags":{"boost":1000000.0}}},"docs":[{"location":"index.html","title":"alismx profile","text":"<p>I'm Alis, a DevOps engineer passionate about open-source, cloud-native technologies, and public health. I'm currently working at Skylight on projects that enable public health agencies to leverage modern, cloud-based software solutions. Feel free to follow me on GitHub or connect with me on LinkedIn. </p> <p> </p> <ul> <li> <p>Skylight Projects</p> </li> <li> <p>CDC Cloud Enablement</p> <ul> <li>Enabling public health agencies with flexible cloud hosting options so they can leverage modern, cloud-based software solutions with fewer costs and maintenance burdens.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>CDC DIBBS</p> <ul> <li>An open-source, modular toolkit designed to automate data processing, reduce manual effort, and address critical data challenges within a modern public health data infrastructure.</li> </ul> </li> <li> <p>CDC SimpleReport</p> <ul> <li>A free tool that makes it easy for non-traditional and under-resourced disease testing sites to record results for diagnostic tests and quickly report data to public health departments.</li> </ul> </li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-work","title":"\ud83d\ude80 My work","text":"<ul> <li>alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>CDCgov/dibbs-aws</li> <li>CDCgov/terraform-aws-dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>CDCgov/dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>CDCgov/dibbs-azure</li> <li>alismx/dibbs-cloud-tools</li> <li>alismx/DevOpsMemes</li> <li>alismx/nomad</li> <li>skylight-hq/dibbs-landing</li> <li>alismx/dibbs-ecr-viewer-playbook</li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-pull-requests","title":"\ud83c\udf31 My pull requests","text":"<ul> <li>chore: regenerate site and update generated files on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>chore: update site navigation, colors, and plugins on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>docs: migrate gitleaks post and add Bandit SAST post on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>docs: migrate blog and docs structure on alismx/alismx.github.io</li> <li>feat(security): add inspector2:Enable and update ECS module ref on CDCgov/dibbs-aws</li> <li>refactor: move SQLi_BODY to count on CDCgov/terraform-aws-dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>fix(ecs): update ECS module ref to commit with WAF fix on CDCgov/dibbs-aws</li> <li>refactor: move CrossSiteScripting_BODY to count on CDCgov/terraform-aws-dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>refactor: restructure ECS README into user-focused deployment guide on CDCgov/dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> <li>feat: add eCR Viewer VM deployment scripts and README rewrite on CDCgov/dibbs-ecr-viewer</li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-gists","title":"\ud83d\udcd3 My gists","text":"<ul> <li>How to: Use qemu-img command to convert between vmdk, raw, qcow2, vdi, vhd, vhdx formats/disk images (qemu-img create, snapshot, resize etc.)</li> <li>Emulating ARM with QEMU on Debian/Ubuntu</li> <li>Debian 12 preseed file</li> <li></li> <li></li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#recent-followers","title":"\ud83d\udc6f Recent followers","text":"<ul> <li>urbantech</li> <li>trinhminhtriet</li> <li>ezgidemirci</li> </ul>"},{"location":"index.html#my-certifications","title":"\ud83d\udcc8 My certifications","text":""},{"location":"index.html#microsoft","title":"Microsoft","text":"<p>Azure Fundamentals</p>"},{"location":"index.html#pluralsight-a-cloud-guru-formerly-linux-academy","title":"Pluralsight (A Cloud Guru, formerly Linux Academy)","text":"<p>Essential Container Concepts</p> <p>LPI Linux Essentials</p> <p>Kubernetes Essentials</p> <p>AWS Concepts</p> <p>AWS Essentials</p> <p>DevOps Essentials</p>"},{"location":"blog/index.html","title":"blog","text":""},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html","title":"DevSecOps: Scan for Secrets in Your Git Repository","text":"<p>Accidentally committed API keys and tokens cause breaches. Gitleaks scans Git history for these patterns.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install gitleaks, configure your repository, run a scan, and add it to your CI pipeline to catch secrets before they reach production.</p>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#install-gitleaks","title":"Install gitleaks","text":"<pre><code>sudo apt install gitleaks\n</code></pre> <p>Verify the install:</p> <pre><code>gitleaks --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#configure-gitleaks","title":"Configure gitleaks","text":"<p>Create a <code>gitleaks.toml</code> file in your repository root:</p> <pre><code>[extend]\nusing = \"github.com/gitleaks/gitleaks\"\n\n[allowlist]\ndescription = \"global allow lists\"\nregexes = [\n    # patterns to allow\n]\n</code></pre> <p>Add a custom rule:</p> <pre><code>[[rules]]\nid = \"my-custom-secret\"\ndescription = \"Custom secret pattern\"\nregex = '''(your-pattern-here)'''\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#scan-your-repository","title":"Scan Your Repository","text":"<pre><code># Full history scan\ngitleaks detect --source .\n\n# Verbose output (shows actual secrets)\ngitleaks detect --source . --verbose\n\n# Verbose output (redacts actual secrets)\ngitleaks detect --source . --verbose --redact\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#add-to-local-git-hooks","title":"Add to local git hooks","text":"<pre><code>#!/bin/sh\n# .git/hooks/pre-commit\n\nsudo apt install gitleaks\ngitleaks detect --source . --verbose --redact /dev/null\n</code></pre> <p>Make it executable:</p> <pre><code>chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-commit\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#add-gitleaks-to-cicd","title":"Add gitleaks to CI/CD","text":"<pre><code>name: gitleaks\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  scan:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v6\n        with:\n          fetch-depth: 0\n      - uses: gitleaks/gitleaks-action@v3\n        env:\n          GITHUB_TOKEN: ${{ secrets.GITHUB_TOKEN }}\n</code></pre>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/09/devsecops-scan-for-secrets-in-your-git-repository.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>Scan the full Git history. People commit secrets and then delete them from current files, but the values remain in commit history.</li> <li>Use <code>--verbose</code> when investigating findings. It reveals the secret value, not just the file and line.</li> <li>Add gitleaks to your CI on pull requests. Preventing the secret from reaching production is cheaper than responding after it does.</li> </ul>","tags":["gitleaks","secrets","sast","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html","title":"DevSecOps: Scan Infrastructure Code for Misconfigurations with Checkov","text":"<p>Infrastructure code often passes syntax checks but contains security misconfigurations. Open buckets, unencrypted databases, overly permissive access policies. Checkov scans IaC files across 20+ formats for these patterns before you deploy.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install checkov, scan your IaC directory, configure your repository, and add it to your CI pipeline to catch infrastructure misconfigurations before they reach production.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#install-checkov","title":"Install checkov","text":"<pre><code>pip install checkov\n</code></pre> <p>Verify:</p> <pre><code>checkov --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#scan-a-project","title":"Scan a project","text":"<p>Basic usage: scan an entire directory recursively:</p> <pre><code>checkov -d /path/to/iac\n</code></pre> <p>Scan a single file:</p> <pre><code>checkov -f /path/to/main.tf\n</code></pre> <p>Checkov groups findings by resource type. AWS findings use <code>CKV_AWS_XX</code> IDs, Azure uses <code>CKV_AZURE_XX</code>, Kubernetes uses <code>CKV_K8S_XX</code>, and so on.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#understand-the-checks","title":"Understand the checks","text":"<p>Checkov has 750+ built-in policies across 20+ IaC types. It parses HCL-based files (.tf, .tofu, .hcl) with the same rules since both Terraform and OpenTofu use HCL.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#iac-formats","title":"IaC formats","text":"IaC Type Format Suppression Terraform / OpenTofu .tf, .tofu, .hcl, .tfvars <code># checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_21: reason</code> Kubernetes .yaml, .json <code>checkov.io/skip1: CKV_K8S_20=reason</code> CloudFormation .json, .yaml, .yml, .template <code># checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_1: reason</code> Dockerfile Named files (Dockerfile, Dockerfile.*, dockerfile) <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_DOCKER_1: reason</code> Bicep .bicep <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AZURE_1: reason</code> ARM Templates .json CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) Ansible .yaml, .yml, .json <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_ANSIBLE_1: reason</code> Argo Workflows .yaml <code>checkov.io/skip1: CKV_ARGO_1=reason</code> Serverless Framework .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_1: reason</code> AWS SAM .yaml, .yml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AWS_1: reason</code> OpenAPI .yaml, .json <code>// checkov:skip=CKV_OPENAPI_1: reason</code> Azure Pipelines .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_AZUREPIPELINES_1: reason</code>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#auto-detected","title":"Auto-detected","text":"IaC Type Format Suppression Helm Auto-detected by Chart.yaml presence Via <code>#checkov:skip</code> on templates Kustomize Auto-detected by kustomization.yaml presence Via <code>#checkov:skip</code> on templates AWS CDK Synthesized from .ts, .js, .py (cdk synth to JSON first) CDK construct metadata","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#vcs-configuration","title":"VCS configuration","text":"<p>Checkov evaluates organization and repository settings from the respective APIs, not from code files. You need to provide a personal access token for each platform.</p> IaC Type Format Suppression GitHub Actions .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_GITHUB_1: reason</code> GitHub Configuration .json (fetched from GitHub API) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) GitLab CI .yml, .yaml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_GITLABCI_1: reason</code> GitLab Configuration .json (fetched from GitLab API) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) Bitbucket Pipelines .yml <code>#checkov:skip=CKV_CIRCLECIPIPELINES_1: reason</code> Bitbucket Configuration .json (fetched from Bitbucket API) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) <p>See the GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket scan examples for required environment variables.</p> <p>See the GitHub, GitLab, and Bitbucket documentation for required environment variables.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#other","title":"Other","text":"IaC Type Format Suppression SCA .lock, .json, .txt, .xml, .toml (varies by language) File-level comment in lock file Git History (repository commit history, not a file format) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) Terraform Plan .tfplan (Terraform plan output, not source) CLI only (<code>--skip-check</code>) <p>Checkov's full policy index is auto-generated from the source and available at 5.Policy Index.</p> <p>Notes on auto-detected types: Helm and Kustomize auto-detect config file presence, then template out to Kubernetes manifests for scanning. AWS CDK requires running <code>cdk synth</code> to generate a CloudFormation JSON template, which checkov then scans.</p> <p>VCS configuration types (GitHub Configuration, GitLab Configuration, Bitbucket Configuration) fetch organization settings from their respective APIs and evaluate them as JSON data. You must provide a personal access token for each platform.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#configuration-files","title":"Configuration files","text":"<p>You can configure checkov with a YAML file in the root of your repo:</p> <pre><code># checkov.yaml\ncheck:\n  skip-check:\n    - CKV_AWS_21\n    - CKV_AWS_34\n\nsoft-fail: true\ncompact: true\n</code></pre> <p>The <code>skip-check</code> list matches <code>--skip-check</code> on the command line. The <code>soft-fail</code> flag makes checkov exit with code 0 even when findings exist, which is useful when you want CI to pass but still report findings. The <code>compact</code> flag collapses duplicate findings into a single line.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#output-formats","title":"Output formats","text":"<p>Checkov supports several output formats. The default is text. For CI integration, use JSON, SARIF, or JUnit XML.</p> <pre><code># Default: human-readable text\ncheckov -d .\n\n# JSON (parseable in CI)\ncheckov -d . -o json -o findings.json\n\n# SARIF (GitHub Code Scanning, GitLab SAST)\ncheckov -d . -o sarif -o findings.sarif\n\n# JUnit XML (for CI systems)\ncheckov -d . -o junitxml -o findings.xml\n</code></pre> <p>SARIF integrates with GitHub Code Scanning and GitLab SAST which renders findings as in-line annotations on the source files.</p>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#add-to-cicd","title":"Add to CI/CD","text":"<p>The <code>checkov-action</code> with the <code>github_failed_only</code> output format reports findings as inline checks on the pull request.</p> <pre><code># .github/workflows/checkov.yml\nname: Checkov\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  checkov:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - name: Run Checkov\n        uses: bridgecrewio/checkov-action@v12\n        with:\n          output_format: sarif,github_failed_only\n          output_file_path: console,results.sarif\n      - name: Upload SARIF file\n        uses: github/codeql-action/upload-sarif@v2\n        if: success() || failure()\n        with:\n          sarif_file: results.sarif\n</code></pre>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-scan-infrastructure-code-for-misconfigurations-with-checkov.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>Use <code>--skip-check</code> for known misconfigurations that have a valid justification. Don't skip checks blindly. Skip them only when the resource is intentionally configured that way.</li> <li>Use <code>checkov:skip</code> comments to suppress individual findings in the code. Always explain why.</li> <li>The <code>checkov-action</code> GitHub Action renders findings as PR checks. It's cleaner than parsing JSON output and formatting it manually.</li> <li>Run checkov in CI on pull requests. Preventing a misconfiguration from reaching production is cheaper than fixing it after the fact.</li> </ul>","tags":["checkov","iac","terraform","kubernetes","cloudformation","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html","title":"DevSecOps: Run SAST on Python Code with Bandit","text":"<p>Insecure Python patterns (<code>eval()</code>, <code>os.system()</code>, hardcoded credentials) end up in production repos. Bandit scans Python code to find them.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install Bandit, configure your repository, run a scan, and add it to your CI pipeline to catch security issues before they reach production.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#install-bandit","title":"Install Bandit","text":"<pre><code>pip install bandit\n</code></pre> <p>The apt package is outdated at 1.6.2. Use pip for the current version (1.9.4).</p> <p>Verify:</p> <pre><code>bandit --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#extras","title":"Extras","text":"<p>Bandit has optional extras for additional functionality:</p> <pre><code># SARIF output formatter (for GitHub and other tools)\npip install bandit[sarif]\n\n# Baseline comparison (ignore known-vulnerabilities)\npip install bandit[baseline]\n\n# TOML configuration support\npip install bandit[toml]\n</code></pre> <p>These aren't needed to start. They become useful once you're past the basic scanning phase.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#understand-the-rule-ids","title":"Understand the rule IDs","text":"<p>Bandit uses alphanumeric rule IDs. The letter prefix groups them by category:</p> Prefix Category What it checks B1xx Assertion <code>assert</code> statements in production code B2xx Exec/eval <code>eval()</code>, <code>exec()</code>, <code>pickle</code> usage B3xx Blacklist calls Dangerous function calls (shell injection, SSL bypass) B4xx Blacklist imports Insecure imports (pickle, xml, subprocess with shell=True) B5xx Crypto Weak crypto algorithms (MD5, DES, RC4) B6xx OS <code>os.system()</code>, <code>subprocess</code> with shell=True, command injection B7xx Network SSL/TLS misconfiguration, insecure protocols <p>The most commonly skipped rules are B101 (assert statements) and B602 (os.system). Whether you skip them depends on your code. If you're running Bandit on test files or production code with assertions, they'll generate noise.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#scan-a-project","title":"Scan a project","text":"<p>Basic usage:</p> <pre><code># Single file\nbandit single_file.py\n\n# Entire directory\nbandit -r /path/to/project\n\n# Limit context lines shown in output\nbandit examples/*.py -n 3 --severity-level high\n</code></pre> <p>Skip specific rules by ID:</p> <pre><code>bandit -r . --skip B101,B602\n</code></pre> <p>Skip specific directories:</p> <pre><code>bandit -r . --exclude ./tests/\n</code></pre> <p>Scan from stdin:</p> <pre><code>cat examples/imports.py | bandit -\n</code></pre> <p>You can filter by severity or confidence level:</p> <pre><code># Medium security level\nbandit -r . -ll\n\n# High security + High confidence\nbandit -r . -lll -iii\n\n# By severity name\nbandit -r . --severity-level high\n\n# By confidence name\nbandit -r . --confidence-level high\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#output-formats","title":"Output formats","text":"<p>Bandit supports several output formats. The default is plain text. For CI integration, use JSON or SARIF.</p> <pre><code># Default: human-readable text\nbandit -r .\n\n# JSON (parseable in CI)\nbandit -r . -f json -o findings.json\n\n# SARIF (for GitHub and other tools)\nbandit -r . -f sarif -o findings.sarif\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#configuration-files","title":"Configuration files","text":"<p>You can configure Bandit with a YAML or TOML file, or an INI file called <code>.bandit</code>.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#yaml-recommended-works-with-all-extras","title":"YAML (recommended, works with all extras)","text":"<pre><code># bandit.yaml\nskips:\n  - B101\n  - B602\n\nexclude_dirs:\n  - tests\n  - migrations\n</code></pre> <pre><code>bandit -c bandit.yaml -r .\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#toml","title":"TOML","text":"<pre><code># pyproject.toml\n[tool.bandit]\nexclude_dirs = [\"tests\", \"migrations\"]\nskips = [\"B101\", \"B602\"]\n</code></pre> <pre><code>bandit -c pyproject.toml -r .\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#config-generator","title":"Config generator","text":"<p>Bandit ships <code>bandit-config-generator</code> which generates a full configuration file with all detected plugins:</p> <pre><code>bandit-config-generator -s B101,B602 -o bandit.yaml\n</code></pre> <p>This is useful for understanding what plugins are available and their default settings. Edit the output down to what your project actually needs.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#suppress-individual-findings","title":"Suppress individual findings","text":"<p>If a line triggers a finding that you've reviewed and determined is safe, add <code># nosec</code>:</p> <pre><code># This hash is for unique IDs only, not security\nthe_hash = md5(data).hexdigest() # nosec\n</code></pre> <p>The whole line gets suppressed. If you only want to suppress specific checks on that line, name them:</p> <pre><code>self.process = subprocess.Popen('/bin/ls *', shell=True)  # nosec B602, B607\n</code></pre> <p>You can use full test names instead of IDs:</p> <pre><code>assert yaml.load(\"{}\") == []  # nosec assert_used\n</code></pre> <p>Always add a comment explaining why you're suppressing the finding. Without context, future reviewers won't know if the suppression is intentional or lazy.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#baseline-ignore-known-vulnerabilities","title":"Baseline: ignore known vulnerabilities","text":"<p>If you have findings that are known and not currently actionable (e.g., a cleartext password in a unit test), generate a baseline and pass it to subsequent scans:</p> <pre><code># Generate baseline\nbandit -f json -o baseline.json -r .\n\n# Subsequent scans ignore baseline findings\nbandit -b baseline.json -f json -r .\n</code></pre> <p>This is cleaner than suppressing individual lines when you have dozens of known-vulnerabilities.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#add-to-local-git-hooks","title":"Add to local git hooks","text":"<p>Add Bandit as a pre-commit git hook:</p> <pre><code>#!/bin/sh\n# .git/hooks/pre-commit\n\npip install -q bandit\nbandit -r . -ll -f json -o /dev/null\n</code></pre> <p>Make it executable:</p> <pre><code>chmod +x .git/hooks/pre-commit\n</code></pre>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#add-to-cicd","title":"Add to CI/CD","text":"<pre><code># .github/workflows/bandit.yml\nname: Bandit SAST\non: [pull_request]\njobs:\n  scan:\n    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n    steps:\n      - uses: actions/checkout@v4\n      - name: Set up Python\n        uses: actions/setup-python@v5\n        with:\n          python-version: '3.12'\n      - name: Install Bandit\n        run: pip install bandit[sarif]\n      - name: Run Bandit\n        run: bandit -r . -f sarif -o bandit-results.sarif\n      - name: Upload SARIF\n        uses: github/codeql-action/upload-sarif@v3\n        with:\n          sarif_file: bandit-results.sarif\n</code></pre> <p>The SARIF output format integrates directly with GitHub's code scanning UI, which is nicer than trying to parse plain-text results.</p>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/10/devsecops-run-sast-on-python-code-with-bandit.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li>Bandit catches the common things: <code>eval()</code>, <code>os.system()</code>, weak crypto, hardcoded secrets</li> <li>Use <code>--severity-level</code> and <code>--confidence-level</code> to control finding noise</li> <li><code># nosec</code> suppresses a line. Name the specific checks if you only want to suppress certain ones</li> <li>Baseline files are cleaner than suppressing individual findings for known-vulnerabilities</li> <li>SARIF output integrates with GitHub code scanning</li> <li>Local git hooks catch findings before they reach CI</li> <li>The apt version is stale. Use pip for the current rule set.</li> <li>Always explain why when you skip a rule or add a <code># nosec</code> comment</li> </ul>","tags":["bandit","sast","python","github","git","security","ci"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html","title":"DevSecOps: Manage Terraform Versions with tfenv","text":"<p>State file incompatibility between Terraform versions breaks your pipelines. tfenv manages multiple versions so you can pin a specific version, switch between them, and keep CI aligned with your local environment.</p> <p>TL;DR: Install tfenv, switch to the version your project needs, and pin it in CI to prevent version drift between local and remote environments.</p>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","version","github","ci","git"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#install-tfenv","title":"Install tfenv","text":"<pre><code>git clone https://github.com/tfutils/tfenv.git ~/.tfenv\n</code></pre> <p>Add it to your shell profile:</p> <pre><code># ~/.bashrc, ~/.zshrc, etc.\nexport PATH=\"$HOME/.tfenv/bin:$PATH\"\n</code></pre> <p>Verify:</p> <pre><code>tfenv --version\n</code></pre>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","version","github","ci","git"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#check-available-versions","title":"Check available versions","text":"<pre><code># All available versions\ntfenv list-remote\n\n# Filter for a specific major version (1)\ntfenv list-remote | grep \"^1\\.\"\n</code></pre> <p>Terraform uses semantic versioning: breaking changes only happen between major versions. Minor and patch updates are compatible with existing state.</p>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","version","github","ci","git"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#switch-versions","title":"Switch versions","text":"<pre><code># Install a specific version\ntfenv install 1.15.0\n\n# List installed versions\ntfenv list\n\n# Switch to a version \ntfenv use 1.15.0\n\n# Write current version to .terraform-version\ntfenv pin\n</code></pre> <p>This file is tracked in git. Anyone who runs <code>tfenv use</code> (or <code>terraform</code> with tfenv installed) will use the pinned version.</p> <pre><code># Reads from .terraform-version by default\ntfenv use\n</code></pre>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","version","github","ci","git"]},{"location":"blog/2026/06/11/devsecops-manage-terraform-versions-with-tfenv.html#takeaways","title":"Takeaways","text":"<ul> <li><code>.terraform-version</code> is tracked in git, so the whole team uses the same Terraform version. This is the source of truth.</li> <li><code>tfenv use</code> reads from <code>.terraform-version</code> by default. <code>tfenv pin</code> writes to it. The primary workflow is both without arguments.</li> <li>Terraform uses semantic versioning: breaking changes only happen between major versions. Minor and patch updates are safe.</li> </ul>","tags":["tfenv","terraform","version","github","ci","git"]},{"location":"blog/archive/2026.html","title":"2026","text":""},{"location":"blog/category/devsecops.html","title":"DevSecOps","text":""}]}